      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey quick question, i'm running a small clothing boutique and i keep hearing about \"inventory turnover ratio\". how do i actually calculate that and what does a low number mean for my shop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A low inventory turnover ratio is a sign that your shop is holding onto too many old, unworn, or slightly mismatched pieces of clothing, which is a major cause of financial loss. It's a common problem for small boutiques, but it's easily solved by keeping your stock fresh and moving things out quickly.\n\nTo calculate the ratio, you simply divide your total cost of goods sold by your average inventory value over the same period. If you're not sure how to get your average inventory, you can take the sum of your beginning and ending inventory and divide by two.\n\nA low number means you're not selling your clothes fast enough, which leads to dead stock. It's a great time to check your pricing, consider a new marketing campaign, or perhaps just give your customers a little more time to enjoy your unique collection.",
      "source": "target",
